<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-03T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-03T10:00:00-05:00" n="92" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d92">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/1900: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-03T23:00:00+08:00">October 3, 1939—11
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 3—10:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>885. Reference to Department’s telegram No. 379, September 30, 1
                                p.m., and 382, October 2, 8 p.m. I am seeing Japanese Consul General
                                tomorrow and leaving with him a memorandum.<note n="91" xml:id="d92fn91">British representations were made October
                                    7.</note> Embassy at Tokyo has been requested to take action.
                                American Commandant tells me British military not yet prepared to
                                take action regarding proposals for revision of defense plan.
                                Growing indications suggest that their position when finally
                                determined upon may be weak.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Chungking, Peiping and Tokyo.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>